irements.\r\n\r\nJust last month, while scheduling an assessment at a factory in China, Omega was asked for some informal advice.Â  The factory was working with a separate client who permits subcontracting on the basis that the Tier II site produces a recent audit report verifying that it meets its responsible sourcing standards.Â  While the approach is commendable, the policy lacked the pragmatism to be effective. Â The site hadnâ€™t been audited before and, due to production lead times, it wasnâ€™t possible to organize an audit or identify a new subcontractor. Â Further, even if an audit was performed the Tier II factory almost certainly wouldnâ€™t meet the clientâ€™s standard.Â  The factory was concerned about losing the order, and asked if Omega knew of an alternative site. This suggests that if it couldnâ€™t identity a compliant one it may even resort to attempting to bribe the clientâ€™s auditor.\r\n\r\nWhile attempted bribery is completely unacceptable, Omega did sympathize with the supplierâ€™s predicament. Perhaps the most practical solution would be to hold Tier II sites to a less comprehensive standard where they are assessed for zero tolerance issues only. Another solution would be for brands and retailers to collaborate around a number of Tier II embroidery factories, for example? With more stable commercial relationships, these sites would then be in a better position to make the requisite investment in workplace conditions driving responsible sourcing and supply chain transparency from the ground up.\r\n\r\nOmega has vast experience in managing compliance programs across subcontractors. Should you require information on our services do please <a href="https://local.omega.com/contact/">contact us</a>.', 'Case Study: Unauthorized Subcontracting in Chinese Supply Chains', 'The majority of Chinese factories subcontract at least one production process to a separate, undisclosed, manufacturer.  This poses a significant risk to responsible sourcing programs.